The simulation workflow follows MIDASim's three-step process:
\enumerate{
\item \strong{Setup}: \code{MIDASim.setup()} learns the template's taxon abundance
distributions, sparsity patterns, and taxon-taxon correlations.
\item \strong{Modify}: \code{MIDASim.modify()} introduces DA effects by creating
sample-specific relative abundances. For case samples (where
\code{fact == condition}), selected taxa are multiplied by
\code{exp(effect_size)}, then renormalized to sum to 1.
\item \strong{Simulate}: \code{MIDASim()} generates realistic count data preserving
the template's correlation structure.
}

This approach is superior to simple count multiplication because:
\itemize{
\item Taxon-taxon correlations are preserved
\item Sparsity patterns are realistic
\item Library sizes follow realistic distributions
\item The DA signal is embedded in the data generation process
}
}
